He says he spent $ 300 million on his art business this year . 
Mr. Morishita 's main business certainly appears to be thriving , although he wo n't disclose numbers . 
According to Teikoku Data Bank Ltd. , which tracks company earnings , Aichi 's revenue rose 15 % to 49.3 billion yen -LRB- $ 348.4 million -RRB- in the year ended February . 
That is , if the company reported results correctly . 
The Asahi Shimbun , a Japanese daily , last month reported that Aichi revised its tax calculations after being challenged for allegedly failing to report all of its income to tax authorities over a two-year period . 
The small , wiry Mr. Morishita comes across as an outspoken man of the world . 
But when asked what exactly he does in business , he immediately takes offense . 
`` Are you stupid ? '' he snaps . 
When a small company goes belly-up , for instance , the gossipy weekly magazines are often quick to link the demise with Aichi . 
Mr. Morishita scoffs at those stories , as well as the ones connecting him to the Japanese mob . 
The seventh child of a store owner in Aichi prefecture , Mr. Morishita started out in the textile business . 
The gruff financier recently started socializing in upper-class circles . 
He also leads an opulent life style . 
Even in Denenchofu , one of Tokyo 's richest neighborhoods , Mr. Morishita 's splashy brick manor -- one of some 10 houses he owns -- outshines the neighbors ' . 
Although Mr. Morishita says little about his business , he offers one rule to success : Never gamble too far . 
`` I quit after one try , whether I win or lose , '' he says . 
Mr. Morishita says he intends to expand his business to many other areas at home and abroad . 
He 'll be there wherever there 's money to be made , laughs Mr. Kori , the secretary . 
